The strongest finding was subgroup synergy among feature_025, feature_015, and feature_023. Pairwise additive interactions were large and positive: feature_025 x feature_015 difference-in-differences ${rNum(inter(f.f025, f.f015).effect)}, feature_025 x feature_023 ${rNum(inter(f.f025, f.f023).effect)}, and feature_015 x feature_023 ${rNum(inter(f.f015, f.f023).effect)}, all highly significant. Patients with all three favorable features present had a ${rate(diffBetween(f.tripleYes, f.tripleNo).p1)} response rate versus ${rate(diffBetween(f.tripleYes, f.tripleNo).p0)} when all three were absent, a risk difference of ${rNum(diffBetween(f.tripleYes, f.tripleNo).effect)}.

Resistance-like heterogeneity was evident. feature_001 significantly weakened the feature_025 and feature_015 associations (interaction estimates ${rNum(inter(f.f025, f.f001).effect)} and ${rNum(inter(f.f015, f.f001).effect)}). feature_032 similarly weakened the feature_025 and feature_023 associations (interaction estimates ${rNum(inter(f.f025, f.f032).effect)} and ${rNum(inter(f.f023, f.f032).effect)}). In contrast, the feature_027=0 by feature_025 interaction and the feature_004>3 by feature_025 interaction were not significant, suggesting those effects were more additive than synergistic.

